events.description: The old St. Peter's Basilica is consecrated by Pope Sylvester I.
events.html: • 326 – The old St. Peter's Basilica is consecrated by Pope Sylvester I.[1]

events.description: The Visigoths, led by king Alaric I, cross the Alps and invade northern Italy.
events.html: • 401 – The Visigoths, led by king Alaric I, cross the Alps and invade northern Italy.[2]

events.description: The Council of Clermont begins: called by Pope Urban II, it led to the First Crusade to the Holy Land.
events.html: • 1095 – The Council of Clermont begins: called by Pope Urban II, it led to the First Crusade to the Holy Land.[3]

events.description: Maginulfo is elected Antipope Sylvester IV in opposition to Pope Paschal II.
events.html: • 1105 – Maginulfo is elected Antipope Sylvester IV in opposition to Pope Paschal II.[4]

events.description: Pope Innocent III excommunicates Holy Roman Emperor Otto IV for invading the Kingdom of Sicily after promising to recognize papal control over it.
events.html: • 1210 – Pope Innocent III excommunicates Holy Roman Emperor Otto IV for invading the Kingdom of Sicily after promising to recognize papal control over it.[5]

events.description: Pope Boniface VIII issues the Papal bull Unam sanctam, claiming spiritual supremacy for the papacy.
events.html: • 1302 – Pope Boniface VIII issues the Papal bull Unam sanctam, claiming spiritual supremacy for the papacy.[6]

events.description: St Elizabeth's flood: A dike in the Grote Hollandse Waard in the Netherlands breaks, killing about 10,000 people.
events.html: • 1421 – St Elizabeth's flood: A dike in the Grote Hollandse Waard in the Netherlands breaks, killing about 10,000 people.[7]

events.description: Christopher Columbus first sights the island now known as Puerto Rico.
events.html: • 1493 – Christopher Columbus first sights the island now known as Puerto Rico.[8]

events.description: Tiryaki Hasan Pasha, an Ottoman provincial governor, routs the Habsburg forces commanded by Archduke Ferdinand II of Austria who were besieging Nagykanizsa.
events.html: • 1601 – Tiryaki Hasan Pasha, an Ottoman provincial governor, routs the Habsburg forces commanded by Archduke Ferdinand II of Austria who were besieging Nagykanizsa.[9]

events.description: The new St. Peter's Basilica in Rome is consecrated.
events.html: • 1626 – The new St. Peter's Basilica in Rome is consecrated.[10]

events.description: The future Frederick the Great of Prussia is granted a pardon by his father and is released from confinement.
events.html: • 1730 – The future Frederick the Great of Prussia is granted a pardon by his father and is released from confinement.[11]

events.description: The rebuilt debtors' prison, at the Castellania in Valletta, receives the first prisoners.
events.html: • 1760 – The rebuilt debtors' prison, at the Castellania in Valletta, receives the first prisoners.[12]

events.description: The Battle of Vertières, the last major battle of the Haitian Revolution, is fought, leading to the establishment of the Republic of Haiti, the first black republic in the Western Hemisphere.
events.html: • 1803 – The Battle of Vertières, the last major battle of the Haitian Revolution, is fought, leading to the establishment of the Republic of Haiti, the first black republic in the Western Hemisphere.[13]

events.description: In a naval action during the Napoleonic Wars, French frigates defeat British East Indiamen in the Bay of Bengal.
events.html: • 1809 – In a naval action during the Napoleonic Wars, French frigates defeat British East Indiamen in the Bay of Bengal.[14]

events.description: Napoleonic Wars: The Battle of Krasnoi ends in French defeat, but Marshal of France Michel Ney's leadership leads to him becoming known as "the bravest of the brave".
events.html: • 1812 – Napoleonic Wars: The Battle of Krasnoi ends in French defeat, but Marshal of France Michel Ney's leadership leads to him becoming known as "the bravest of the brave".

events.description: King Christian IX of Denmark signs the November constitution that declares Schleswig to be part of Denmark. This is seen by the German Confederation as a violation of the London Protocol and leads to the German–Danish war of 1864.
events.html: • 1863 – King Christian IX of Denmark signs the November constitution that declares Schleswig to be part of Denmark. This is seen by the German Confederation as a violation of the London Protocol and leads to the German–Danish war of 1864.

events.description: An earthquake strikes the Virgin Islands, triggering the largest tsunami witnessed in the Caribbean and killing dozens.
events.html: • 1867 – An earthquake strikes the Virgin Islands, triggering the largest tsunami witnessed in the Caribbean and killing dozens.[15]

events.description: Susan B. Anthony and 14 other women are arrested for voting illegally in the United States presidential election of 1872.
events.html: • 1872 – Susan B. Anthony and 14 other women are arrested for voting illegally in the United States presidential election of 1872.

events.description: In the "day of two noons," American and Canadian railroad companies institute four standard continental time zones, ending the confusion of thousands of local times.
events.html: • 1883 – In the "day of two noons," American and Canadian railroad companies institute four standard continental time zones, ending the confusion of thousands of local times.[16]

events.description: Britain and the United States sign the Hay–Pauncefote Treaty, which nullifies the Clayton–Bulwer Treaty and withdraws British objections to an American-controlled canal in Panama.
events.html: • 1901 – Britain and the United States sign the Hay–Pauncefote Treaty, which nullifies the Clayton–Bulwer Treaty and withdraws British objections to an American-controlled canal in Panama.

events.description: The Hay–Bunau-Varilla Treaty is signed by the United States and Panama, giving the United States exclusive rights over the Panama Canal Zone.
events.html: • 1903 – The Hay–Bunau-Varilla Treaty is signed by the United States and Panama, giving the United States exclusive rights over the Panama Canal Zone.

events.description: Prince Carl of Denmark becomes King Haakon VII of Norway.
events.html: • 1905 – Prince Carl of Denmark becomes King Haakon VII of Norway.

events.description: Two United States warships are sent to Nicaragua after 500 revolutionaries (including two Americans) are executed by order of José Santos Zelaya.
events.html: • 1909 – Two United States warships are sent to Nicaragua after 500 revolutionaries (including two Americans) are executed by order of José Santos Zelaya.

events.description: In their campaign for women's voting rights, hundreds of suffragettes march to the British Parliament in London. Several are beaten by police, newspaper attention embarrasses the authorities, and the march is dubbed Black Friday.
events.html: • 1910 – In their campaign for women's voting rights, hundreds of suffragettes march to the British Parliament in London. Several are beaten by police, newspaper attention embarrasses the authorities, and the march is dubbed Black Friday.[17]

events.description: World War I: First Battle of the Somme: In France, British Expeditionary Force commander Douglas Haig calls off the battle which started on July 1, 1916.
events.html: • 1916 – World War I: First Battle of the Somme: In France, British Expeditionary Force commander Douglas Haig calls off the battle which started on July 1, 1916.

events.description: Latvia declares its independence from Russia.
events.html: • 1918 – Latvia declares its independence from Russia.

events.description: Release of the animated short Steamboat Willie, the first fully synchronized sound cartoon.
events.html: • 1928 – Release of the animated short Steamboat Willie, the first fully synchronized sound cartoon.

events.description: Grand Banks earthquake: Off the south coast of Newfoundland in the Atlantic Ocean, a Richter magnitude 7.2 submarine earthquake, centered on the  Grand Banks, breaks 12 submarine transatlantic telegraph cables and triggers a tsunami that destroys many south coast communities in the Burin Peninsula.
events.html: • 1929 – Grand Banks earthquake: Off the south coast of Newfoundland in the Atlantic Ocean, a Richter magnitude 7.2 submarine earthquake, centered on the Grand Banks, breaks 12 submarine transatlantic telegraph cables and triggers a tsunami that destroys many south coast communities in the Burin Peninsula.

events.description: World War II: German leader Adolf Hitler and Italian Foreign Minister Galeazzo Ciano meet to discuss Benito Mussolini's disastrous Italian invasion of Greece.
events.html: • 1940 – World War II: German leader Adolf Hitler and Italian Foreign Minister Galeazzo Ciano meet to discuss Benito Mussolini's disastrous Italian invasion of Greece.

events.description: World War II: Battle of Berlin: Four hundred and forty Royal Air Force planes bomb Berlin causing only light damage and killing 131. The RAF loses nine aircraft and 53 air crew.
events.html: • 1943 – World War II: Battle of Berlin: Four hundred and forty Royal Air Force planes bomb Berlin causing only light damage and killing 131. The RAF loses nine aircraft and 53 air crew.

events.description: The Popular Socialist Youth is founded in Cuba.
events.html: • 1944 – The Popular Socialist Youth is founded in Cuba.

events.description: The Ballantyne's Department Store fire in Christchurch, New Zealand, kills 41; it is the worst fire disaster in the history of New Zealand.
events.html: • 1947 – The Ballantyne's Department Store fire in Christchurch, New Zealand, kills 41; it is the worst fire disaster in the history of New Zealand.

events.description: The Iva Valley Shooting occurs after the coal miners of Enugu in Nigeria go on strike over withheld wages; 21 miners are shot dead and 51 are wounded by police under the supervision of the British colonial administration of Nigeria.
events.html: • 1949 – The Iva Valley Shooting occurs after the coal miners of Enugu in Nigeria go on strike over withheld wages; 21 miners are shot dead and 51 are wounded by police under the supervision of the British colonial administration of Nigeria.

events.description: United States President John F. Kennedy sends 18,000 military advisors to South Vietnam.
events.html: • 1961 – United States President John F. Kennedy sends 18,000 military advisors to South Vietnam.[18][19]

events.description: The first push-button telephone goes into service.
events.html: • 1963 – The first push-button telephone goes into service.

events.description: U.S. President Richard Nixon asks the U.S. Congress for $155 million in supplemental aid for the Cambodian government.
events.html: • 1970 – U.S. President Richard Nixon asks the U.S. Congress for $155 million in supplemental aid for the Cambodian government.

events.description: Oman declares its independence from the United Kingdom.
events.html: • 1971 – Oman declares its independence from the United Kingdom.

events.description: The McDonnell Douglas F/A-18 Hornet makes its first flight, at the Naval Air Test Center in Maryland, United States.
events.html: • 1978 – The McDonnell Douglas F/A-18 Hornet makes its first flight, at the Naval Air Test Center in Maryland, United States.[20]

events.description: In Jonestown, Guyana, Jim Jones leads his Peoples Temple to a mass murder–suicide that claimed 918 lives in all, 909 of them in Jonestown itself, including over 270 children.
events.html: • 1978 – In Jonestown, Guyana, Jim Jones leads his Peoples Temple to a mass murder–suicide that claimed 918 lives in all, 909 of them in Jonestown itself, including over 270 children.

events.description: Aeroflot Flight 6833 is hijacked en route from Tbilisi to Leningrad. After returning to Tbilisi, the aircraft is subsequentially raided on the ground, resulting in seven deaths.
events.html: • 1983 – Aeroflot Flight 6833 is hijacked en route from Tbilisi to Leningrad. After returning to Tbilisi, the aircraft is subsequentially raided on the ground, resulting in seven deaths.[21]

events.description: The first comic of Calvin and Hobbes is published in ten newspapers.
events.html: • 1985 – The first comic of Calvin and Hobbes is published in ten newspapers.[22]

events.description: King's Cross fire: In London, 31 people die in a fire at the city's busiest underground station, King's Cross St Pancras.
events.html: • 1987 – King's Cross fire: In London, 31 people die in a fire at the city's busiest underground station, King's Cross St Pancras.

entities.name: King's Cross St Pancras tube station

events.description: Shiite Muslim kidnappers in Lebanon release Anglican Church envoys Terry Waite and Thomas Sutherland.
events.html: • 1991 – Shiite Muslim kidnappers in Lebanon release Anglican Church envoys Terry Waite and Thomas Sutherland.

events.description: After an 87-day siege, the Croatian city of Vukovar capitulates to the besieging Yugoslav People's Army and allied Serb paramilitary forces.
events.html: • 1991 – After an 87-day siege, the Croatian city of Vukovar capitulates to the besieging Yugoslav People's Army and allied Serb paramilitary forces.

events.description: The autonomous Croatian Community of Herzeg-Bosnia, which would in 1993 become a republic, was established in Bosnia and Herzegovina.
events.html: • 1991 – The autonomous Croatian Community of Herzeg-Bosnia, which would in 1993 become a republic, was established in Bosnia and Herzegovina.[23]

events.description: In the United States, the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) is approved by the House of Representatives.
events.html: • 1993 – In the United States, the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) is approved by the House of Representatives.

events.description: In South Africa, 21 political parties approve a new constitution, expanding voting rights and ending white minority rule.
events.html: • 1993 – In South Africa, 21 political parties approve a new constitution, expanding voting rights and ending white minority rule.

events.description: A fire occurs on a train traveling through the Channel Tunnel from France to England causing several injuries and damaging approximately 500 metres (1,600 ft) of tunnel.
events.html: • 1996 – A fire occurs on a train traveling through the Channel Tunnel from France to England causing several injuries and damaging approximately 500 metres (1,600 ft) of tunnel.

events.description: At Texas A&M University, the Aggie Bonfire collapses killing 12 students and injuring 27 others.
events.html: • 1999 – At Texas A&M University, the Aggie Bonfire collapses killing 12 students and injuring 27 others.

events.description: Iraq disarmament crisis: United Nations weapons inspectors led by Hans Blix arrive in Iraq.
events.html: • 2002 – Iraq disarmament crisis: United Nations weapons inspectors led by Hans Blix arrive in Iraq.

events.description: The Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court rules 4–3 in Goodridge v. Department of Public Health that the state's ban on same-sex marriage is unconstitutional and gives the state legislature 180 days to change the law making Massachusetts the first state in the United States to grant marriage rights to same-sex couples.
events.html: • 2003 – The Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court rules 4–3 in Goodridge v.
